WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.429 --> 00:00:02.710
Film Courage: Can you take us through the
process of how you pitched to ABC?

00:00:02.710 --> 00:00:09.020
Jim Agnew, Screenwriter: Yes, this is a question
I get asked a lot is TV projects are very

00:00:09.020 --> 00:00:15.200
different than film. TV you don't have to
have a pilot...let me rephrase that... you

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:20.450
have write out a pilot if you don't have a
history of writing (if you don't have a track

00:00:20.450 --> 00:00:25.040
record and haven't sold anything). Now if
you have, you don't have to write a pilot,

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.400
you have to write a pitch. But for most people
who are coming up you have to actually write

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:34.300
the pilot for the show. What you do is you
write a pilot for a TV show it's whether it's

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:39.570
30 pages 60 pages you write that pilot episode
and then you write a TV pitch now the pitch

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:44.840
is only is would be a verbal pitch you would
pitch which is only 10 minutes long and all

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:50.140
you cover is what the show's about the characters
the beats and the pilot and where it's going

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:56.250
the next few seasons you don't need to write
like a 50-page bible that's not what they

00:00:56.250 --> 00:01:00.829
want to hear TV pitches you're only supposed
to pitch from eight to ten minutes in a room

00:01:00.829 --> 00:01:06.880
and that's it now they they will ask you a
bunch of questions afterwards if they're interested

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:11.540
but you don't need to like do work I see these
people who write these 50 page bibles and

00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:15.680
do all this work and you don't have to do
it that's not how you get a TV show sold TV

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:20.710
show all you need is a like I said the proper
pitch and which is a format which is just

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:25.480
simply about the show the characters a few
beats in the pilot where season one's going

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:29.640
and a few beats for season two that's all
they care about they care about the characters

00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:32.909
more than anything and what the show's about
because you gotta live with those characters

00:01:32.909 --> 00:01:36.880
for years and you have to have a pilot now
more likely if you sell it they're gonna make

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:41.850
you rewrite the whole pilot anyway but you
have to show to the execs that are buying

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:46.049
things that you can perform and write it that's
why if you don't have a track record you have

00:01:46.049 --> 00:01:50.790
to have a pitch and a pilot but if you do
have a track record you don't necessarily

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:53.860
have to write a pilot and they don't even
want you to nowadays because they want to

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:58.470
be involved in in every step of writing the
pilot so not only having great characters

00:01:58.470 --> 00:02:02.770
but characters that can actually grow and
go somewhere how are you factoring any of

00:02:02.770 --> 00:02:07.580
that into this eight-minute pitch or no that's
for them to decide can we go anywhere with

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:12.250
this character no that that goes in your pitch
and when you cover season one and you talk

00:02:12.250 --> 00:02:16.760
about where the show's going like let's say
it's ten episodes you don't go episode by

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:21.580
episode you just say kind of start of season
one middle season one end of season one but

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:26.819
a lot of what you're talking about is where
the relationships go like if character a becomes

00:02:26.819 --> 00:02:31.109
involved with character b and then character
c is upset about that so it's not so much

00:02:31.109 --> 00:02:35.109
plotty as opposed to where the characters
fall into the storyline and how they change

00:02:35.109 --> 00:02:40.180
and adjust because he said TV you're living
it's like being married with these characters

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:44.760
if you have a show and you're gonna do 50
episodes people have to have a reason to keep

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:48.400
coming back to these characters so they have
to grow and change and things have to happen

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:56.389
to them is there a certain time of year when
you can pitch networks yes not let me rephrase

00:02:56.389 --> 00:03:02.069
that not so much anymore it used to be you
would pitch like in I think it was July through

00:03:02.069 --> 00:03:06.810
September because then they would be starting
to set up for the next season but now with

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:11.599
streamers and all that it's kind of year-round
they'll take pictures any time it's only really

00:03:11.599 --> 00:03:18.809
in regards to abc's cbs nbc like the big networks
they still stay more on a schedule because

00:03:18.809 --> 00:03:23.199
they still like to have a lot of shows come
out in September October that kind of time

00:03:23.199 --> 00:03:28.709
frame that they've been doing for decades
but nowadays no not so much now they'll listen

00:03:28.709 --> 00:03:32.489
to pitches almost any time of the year so
it's kind of the streamers have changed all

00:03:32.489 --> 00:03:35.699
that there's no real season to anything

00:03:35.699 --> 00:03:42.959
what are the steps to pitching a TV show a
lot well first of all you've got to get a

00:03:42.959 --> 00:03:46.980
great pitch together and usually you have
a producer you're working with who's taking

00:03:46.980 --> 00:03:52.999
you into the the networks or a company like
the one we when we sold our show to abc we

00:03:52.999 --> 00:04:00.260
had first set it up at Lionsgate so we went
in to abc nbc we went to every network in

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:05.119
one week they make you do it almost like consecutively
so that if one person is interested someone

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:09.639
else will also come aboard and they'll get
a them playing against each other so you almost

00:04:09.639 --> 00:04:15.540
go like you'll get a pitch grid that's like
24 pitches in like four days and you just

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:19.639
go place to place to place do the same thing
but you bring your producers in and the real

00:04:19.639 --> 00:04:25.150
work is working with your producers on the
pitch because when we were very lucky that

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:29.599
the Lionsgate execs had sold a lot of shows
and they were really awesome people and they

00:04:29.599 --> 00:04:35.750
made us do it with them work it over and work
it out and had us they literally time us they'd

00:04:35.750 --> 00:04:40.319
be like okay you only got eight minutes go
and you do the pitch they give you notes you

00:04:40.319 --> 00:04:45.360
rework it you rewrite it and you do it again
and again and they're the final like kind

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:48.689
of decision makers about what the pitch is
going to be like because they're the sellers

00:04:48.689 --> 00:04:55.370
really even though you wrote the show so that
there's going to be back to back this is pitch

00:04:55.370 --> 00:05:01.060
week and so I you plan out your whole sort
of life schedule around that and wardrobe

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:06.520
and coming in with this producer like how
stressful is that to know that you're going

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:12.590
to be on even though writers sort of don't
want that yeah i'm very stressful you just

00:05:12.590 --> 00:05:19.080
have to do it you just do it I mean a pitch
gets easier and easier the more you do it

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:23.580
so the first one or two might be a little
clunky but you just the whole process is to

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:27.080
really give them what the show's about TV
moves super fast faster than phil you get

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:31.169
what the show's about and then you try to
get it after eight minutes into conversation

00:05:31.169 --> 00:05:34.129
get a conversational where hopefully they
ask you a bunch of questions and you talk

00:05:34.129 --> 00:05:38.919
more about the show but you only talk at them
for like a good eight minutes can you talk

00:05:38.919 --> 00:05:44.530
about the bible versus the pitch versus writing
a pilot yes well the the pilot's a pilot whether

00:05:44.530 --> 00:05:50.080
it's a 30 page pilot 60 page pilot which you
have the pitch is like maybe a six or seven

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:54.879
page document maybe less that you you verbally
will read to them in the room you usually

00:05:54.879 --> 00:05:58.740
don't leave it behind you go and because they
like I mean with covet it's a little bit different

00:05:58.740 --> 00:06:02.909
but they've been doing it on zoom you leave
the pitch you do the pitch but you don't leave

00:06:02.909 --> 00:06:09.409
it behind now a bible doesn't get created
until the show has been ordered so a lot of

00:06:09.409 --> 00:06:13.930
people get mixed up on these the bible is
like the bible that explains the characters

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:20.639
the show so it's it adds creates continuity
through the writer's room and from episode

00:06:20.639 --> 00:06:25.250
to episode so a lot of people will be interested
in creating a bible it's like it's an unnecessary

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:30.130
step you don't do that till later in the process
there's only two things you need a pilot and

00:06:30.130 --> 00:06:36.080
a pitch if you're a new kind of screenwriter
wanting to sell a TV show so don't worry about

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:39.719
how do you make the pitch bible or excuse
me don't worry about how you make the bible

00:06:39.719 --> 00:06:45.550
because we get we see that once that once
it's greenlit or once it's getting close to

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:50.020
to being told yes then yeah you're putting
the cart before the horse okay yeah it doesn't

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:54.699
need to be done and most times too like if
they like your pilot more than likely it doesn't

00:06:54.699 --> 00:06:58.620
I mean sometimes they'll be like this is great
let's shoot this but more than likely they're

00:06:58.620 --> 00:07:02.360
going to want you to rewrite the entire pilot
with their input like there's something they

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:06.340
really dig they like it but they're going
to want to do it more their way and if it's

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:12.030
a big network or tnt or amc they know what
they want so they're going to be like this

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:17.290
is great but let's do it this way how much
time did you spend writing on the pitch it

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:23.090
took several passes at it so maybe it was
like about a month where you maybe I mean

00:07:23.090 --> 00:07:27.550
not a month full time but you kind of work
on it send it over work on it send it over

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:34.129
practice it a couple times do it and and just
get everybody's input so we were very lucky

00:07:34.129 --> 00:07:37.310
like I said we had lines get involved which
there were several execs so they would all

00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:43.009
hear it and they'd put in their two cents
or say justice changed that that's great so

00:07:43.009 --> 00:07:47.509
yeah it's like a sales process it's it's a
creative process but it's also like selling

00:07:47.509 --> 00:07:51.889
something so that's a little bit different
of a mindset so you have those eight minutes

00:07:51.889 --> 00:07:55.999
but then what about the talking points that
are more conversational afterwards are you

00:07:55.999 --> 00:08:00.940
preparing if they ask me this then i'm going
to say that yes we would always write down

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:08.169
some talking points just to have them as additional
things but usually they would ask enough questions

00:08:08.169 --> 00:08:13.270
that it would get conversational and you would
you would encourage it and try to talk about

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:18.300
it and also we brought in a few visual presentation
things too like boards that had kind of the

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:22.990
world and some character stuff so we know
we realized really quickly that if you bring

00:08:22.990 --> 00:08:28.080
those in it's kind of uncomfortable for if
you're pitching to five or six execs for them

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:32.380
to just stare at you the whole time for them
so if you have like tone boards and things

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:37.360
they can look away and I think it makes it
more relaxing for them too because it's a

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:41.339
very unnatural thing for you just to be talking
at somebody and then just looking at you the

00:08:41.339 --> 00:08:45.800
whole time so and the tone boards made it
more conversational but yeah we actually after

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:50.430
one or two of those started writing out talking
points that kept coming up and things to add

00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:57.620
on top of the pitch that were like more conversational
so by the by the 23rd pitch you had it down

00:08:57.620 --> 00:09:02.490
so well that you were like why didn't I do
it this way to start out but yeah a little

00:09:02.490 --> 00:09:06.920
bit you get you get really good at by the
time you're done so yeah what other materials

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:17.760
are needed to pitch a network show it depends
it's i've heard some TV execs say like thank

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:24.279
god you didn't bring in a visual presentation
with the the the monitors and all the stuff

00:09:24.279 --> 00:09:30.680
and because they see so many of those so I
don't think it's really necessary because

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:34.630
these are smart executives if you're pitching
to a TV exec at Netflix or somewhere they

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:41.620
know how TV works and they know if it's a
show so I it helps depends if you're world

00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:48.070
building then maybe it might help a little
bit more but if it's like a drama in the midwest

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:52.240
they get it they you don't have to show them
this looks what uncle Charlie looks like and

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:56.500
this is they know so so you don't really need
to bring money but you have to have just a

00:09:56.500 --> 00:10:02.089
really solid quick pitch and and and back
it up and be able to answer any questions

00:10:02.089 --> 00:10:06.460
they have too and the weird thing is sometimes
they don't ask anything and they're the ones

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:09.529
who buy it so you never know sometimes they'll
ask a million questions you're like oh that

00:10:09.529 --> 00:10:16.440
went great and then they pass so that's pretty
much what you got to do is just just follow

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:21.329
your your what you think is best for that
certain type of show obviously if it was something

00:10:21.329 --> 00:10:27.360
based on ip you would bring in vip if it was
a comic book you'd bring in big blow ups of

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.949
the comic book and go these are our characters
but if it's a small intimate thing you would

00:10:30.949 --> 00:10:36.430
I don't think you need to do that how many
times have you pitched a TV show pitched several

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:43.990
that one sold a couple sometimes they don't
sell and for various reasons like maybe somebody

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:51.080
else just announced a show that was very similar
so that happens as well and pitched a couple

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:55.910
where we got hired to write pilots but they
never got on air so probably like five or

00:10:55.910 --> 00:11:02.040
six times and two or three of them sold but
it's becoming more and more really competitive

00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:06.459
as of late because now everyone's in TV a
couple years ago was a little bit easier now

00:11:06.459 --> 00:11:11.079
they want you to bring a whole package in
to pitch a TV show right now you kind of need

00:11:11.079 --> 00:11:17.930
to bring in a director of the pilot the showrunner
the the the producers who are they want big

00:11:17.930 --> 00:11:23.450
producers to kind of get it going so it's
become much more competitive than was a couple

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:29.060
years ago can you talk about how you actually
got in the room did someone that brought you

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:35.320
in well I was fortunate enough that that I
was with paradigm agency at the time and had

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:40.230
an amazing TV agent rich rogers and he did
it all he just said look I love this pilot

00:11:40.230 --> 00:11:45.470
you guys are going to sell it and let's go
to production companies first so we did that

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:50.860
we went to six or seven production companies
Lionsgate paid paid us and bought the project

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:54.800
and then became our producers and then we
went out and then Lionsgate sets you up with

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:59.709
the the networks and the so it's a two-step
